AGI - The day of the earth was created in 1970, when the environmentalist movements were still at their origins, from the United Nations, which established that one should celebrate a month and a day after the equinox of spring, then on April 22. At the origin of the initiative there is the environmentalist theory of the American biologist Rachel Carson>, author of the silent Spring text in 1962; until then the environmental sensitivity was almost absent in the United States as well as in the rest of the industrialized world. Subsequently, the issue became political until the establishment of the day, which led to the creation of the United States Environmental Protection Agency and the approval of other first environmental laws, including the National Environmental Education Act, the Employment Safety and Health Act, and the Clean Air Act.
&nbsp;
Two years after the congress approved the Clean Water Act. The most important international climate agreement, the one reached in Paris in December 2015 at Cop21 to limit the increase of the Earth's temperature within 1.5 degrees compared to the pre-industrial level, was opened to the signature of the Countries Onu in a "day of the earth", on 22 April 2016.&nbsp;
&nbsp;
This year the UN, which in English calls her "mother earth's day", emphasizes that "Mother Earth is clearly urging an invitation to action. Nature is suffering. The oceans fill in plastic and become more acidic. The extreme heat, fires and floods hit millions of people. Climate change, natural changes caused by man and crimes that destroy biodiversity, such as deforestation, change in land use, intensification of agriculture and livestock production or the growing illegal trade of wild species, can speed up the speed of destruction of the planet."
&nbsp;
The UN also recalls that today's "is the third Earth Day celebrated within the UN Decade for Restoration of Ecosystems. Ecosystems support the whole life on Earth. The healthier our ecosystems, the healthier the planet and its inhabitants. Restoration of our damaged ecosystems will help to end poverty, combat climate change and prevent mass extinction. But we will only make it if everyone will make their contribution," is the UN appeal.&nbsp;

